To run a complete GPU benchmark cycle, we will need to use several tools in the following order:

1. get_available_gpus - This will give us the list of available GPUs to choose from. No parameters needed.

2. rent_compute - Once we have the list of GPUs, we can select the best one and rent it. This requires the cluster_name, node_name and gpu_count parameters. We can get the cluster_name and node_name from the output of get_available_gpus. For gpu_count, we can just request 1 GPU since we only need a single GPU for benchmarking.

3. get_gpu_status - After requesting the rental, we need to check the status to see when it is ready. No parameters needed. We will need to call this repeatedly until the status is no longer "starting".

4. ssh_connect - Once the GPU server is ready, we need to connect to it via SSH in order to set up the environment and run the tests. This requires the host, username, and private_key_path parameters. We can get the host from the output of get_gpu_status. The username should be "ubuntu". For the private_key_path, we can use the default SSH_PRIVATE_KEY_PATH from the environment.

5. gpu_health_check - After connecting, the first thing we should do is check the GPU health using this tool. No parameters needed.

6. remote_shell - We will use this multiple times to set up the environment, run the performance tests, and clean up. The only parameter is command, and we will provide the appropriate shell commands for each step.

7. terminate_compute - After everything is done, we need to release the GPU server. This requires the instance_id parameter which we can get from the output of get_gpu_status.

So in summary, we have all the required parameters to make the necessary tool calls. We will need to make the calls in the order specified above, using the outputs of some calls as inputs to later ones.
